## Introduction

In my previous article, [Building with AI Agents](/projects/building-with-ai), I wrote about my experience using Cursor's agent mode to develop components of a 14,500-line personal finance tool. Having enjoyed the velocity of agent-assisted development, I decided to try something a bit more ambitious: setting up a fully autonomous agent framework locally.

Specifically, I wanted to experiment with [OpenClaw](https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw), an open-source framework that runs locally and integrates with LLM APIs and acts as a personal assistant, with full access (if you want) to all your private files and applications. I have an old NAS sitting on my home network which I stored files on, but didn't do much else, and had become a bit of a dumping ground, disorganized, bloated and underutilized. With OpenClaw installed on the NAS, here's how the architecture looks:

