    					"Understood. I have manually configured your system limits directly inside the core configuration file (<code class="bg-zinc-950 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-emerald-300 font-mono text-sm font-semibold">/home/node/.openclaw/openclaw.json</code>) to force cost control.<br/><br/>
    					Here are your new context and compaction settings:<br/>
    					• <strong>Max Context Limit (<code>contextTokens</code>):</strong> Reduced down to <strong>65,000 tokens</strong> (previously 1,000,000). This hard-caps the active workspace and transcript memory size allowed in a single turn.<br/>
    					• <strong>Max History Share (<code>maxHistoryShare</code>):</strong> Set to <strong>0.4 (40%)</strong>. This ensures that after a compaction sweep, older conversation history cannot occupy more than 26,000 tokens of the budget.<br/>
    					• <strong>Reserve Headroom (<code>reserveTokens</code>):</strong> Set to <strong>25,000 tokens</strong>. This reserves a generous buffer for your queries, tool execution outputs, and my responses, preventing mid-turn context overflows."
    				</div>
    			</div>
    		</div>
    	</div>

    	<!-- Explanation -->
    	<div class="mt-4 p-4 md:p-5 rounded-xl bg-zinc-900/45 border border-zinc-800/60 text-base lg:text-xl text-zinc-200 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
    		<strong class="text-zinc-100 font-bold">Explanation:</strong> This was the structural fix that permanently stopped the drain from reoccurring. Under Gemini 3.5 Flash pricing, capping the max context at 65k tokens and dropping the percentage of that for conversation history to 40% (26k tokens) keeps the price of context cached turns (assuming they are frequent enough to benefit) at around $0.03, while a cold start/uncached turn would cost up to ~$0.11, keeping the average cost per turn around or below $0.05 depending on cache efficiency.
    	</div>
    </div>

</div>

