                <span class="px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-mono font-bold tracking-wider uppercase bg-red-950/40 text-red-400 border border-red-800/50 rounded-md">Criminal #4</span>
                <h3 class="text-xl md:text-2xl font-bold text-white group-hover:text-red-400 transition-colors">The Corrupt Cop</h3>
            </div>
            <h4 class="text-base lg:text-lg font-mono text-zinc-400 font-semibold tracking-wide uppercase">The Compaction Trap & Fail-Safe Failure</h4>
            <p class="text-zinc-200 text-base lg:text-xl leading-relaxed pt-1">
                We thought we had a guard on duty, but the protection let us down. OpenClaw's "Auto-Compaction" fail-safe was supposed to police our history and summarize it. Instead, like a corrupt cop sleeping on the job, it failed to compress the structured CSV data (likely because to compress it requires a call to the model and this could well have exceeded the API limit) and threw a system warning: <br><br><code>⚠️ Auto-compaction could not recover this turn</code><br><br>
                The framework kept the raw, uncompressed CSV data mapped to the session, ensuring that the financial damage continued through every subsequent automated Tdarr status check.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

